      <h2 id=for>What is the Distributed Bulletin of Open Science?</h2>

      <p>Distributed Bulletin of Open Science (DBOS) is a tool for dedicating new scientific findings to the public domain.</p>
      <!-- TODO: Scientific _and technical_? -->

      <h2 id=work>How does DBOS work?</h2>

      <p>DBOS gives contributors a <a href=/publish>short online form</a> to fill out with information on new findings they want to contribute to the public domain.  DBOS publishes submissions instantly and verifiably,  both to read online, and to download as well-structured computer data for indexing, searching, and backup.</p>

      <p>Every DBOS publication contains:</p>

      <ul>
        <li>a description of a new scientific finding</li>
        <li>metadata to categorize and contextualize the finding</li>
        <li>a <a href=/declaration>public declaration</a> of commitment to contribute the finding to the public domain</li>
        <li>a <a href=/license>public license</a> for the content of the submission</li>
      </ul>

      <p>These elements work together to do as much as possible, as quickly, cheaply, and easily as possible, to put the finding in the public domain.</p>

      <h2 id=copyright>How does DBOS address copyright?</h2>
      <!-- TODO: Mention database rights, mask rights, etc.? -->

      <p>The <a href=/license>public license</a> that contributors grant for their submissions gives everyone very broad permission to work with DBOS submissions.  The license is similar in scope to a dedication of copyright and similar rights to the public domain, with two conditions to prevent misrepresentation of what was submitted and abuse of the contributor&rsquo;s name.</p>

      <p>The license works much like <a href=https://creativecommons.org>Creative Commons</a> licenses applied to other creative work, like article preprints, but far shorter, quicker to use, and specialized to DBOS-style submissions.</p>
