      <h2 id=patent>How does DBOS address patent?</h2>

      <p>Some new findings may contain patent-eligible &ldquo;inventions&rdquo; under one or many countries&rsquo; laws.  When patents are a concern, DBOS helps scientists win the patent race for the public domain by publishing, immediately and verifiably, with rich metadata that makes it easy to identify as &ldquo;prior art&rdquo; to stop later patent applications.  By combining publication with a <a href=/declaration>commitment to keep the finding open</a> and a <a href=/license>permissive copyright license for the submission</a>, DBOS combines the expediency of defensive publication with the availability of open-access scholarship and the empowerment of open-source licensing.</p>

      <h2 id=race>What's the &ldquo;race to the publisher&rdquo;?</h2>

      <p>Under many countries&rsquo; patent rules, publishing a description that teaches others how to use a legal &ldquo;invention&rdquo; stops anyone, even the one publishing, from receiving a patent later.  Since the <a href=https://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/PLAW-112publ29/content-detail.html>America Invents Act</a>, much the same is now true under United States patent rules, with an exception: the one who published can still receive a patent by applying within one year.</p>

      <p>Under either kind of rule, securing findings for the public domain is a race to publish.  If a patent-seeker applies for a patent or publishes first, a patent can keep the finding closed for twenty years or more.  If anyone contributes to the public domain first&mdash;creating &ldquo;prior art&rdquo; that others can find later&mdash;the work stays open, even if someone else made the same finding earlier.</p>

      <p>DBOS publications meet all the publication requirements for patent-stopping prior art under United States and European patent rules, as well as the rules of many other countries.  The <a href=/license>public license</a> enables others to republish to meet other countries&rsquo; prior art requirements, such as publication in the country, or translation into the local language.</p>

